{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"98d2d63c090518e6ce393cf53614d52565285073edf006b5ca5b417a398b9c04","slug":"ergonomics-and-adaptive-tech","location":"/professional_advice/ergonomics_and_adaptive_tech.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Ergonomics and Disability Accommodations for Programming","content_includes_title":false,"github":"https://github.com/MIDS-at-Duke/dukemids","numbering":{"title":{"offset":1}},"source_url":"https://github.com/MIDS-at-Duke/dukemids/blob/main/professional_advice/ergonomics_and_adaptive_tech.md","edit_url":"https://github.com/MIDS-at-Duke/dukemids/edit/main/professional_advice/ergonomics_and_adaptive_tech.md","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"ergonomics_and_adaptive_tech.md","url":"/build/ergonomics_and_adapt-25adb81267a94490cfef19244d10e23a.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Or: How To Not Hurt Yourself Doing Your Computer Job","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"NXaL4ZaoT7"}],"identifier":"or-how-to-not-hurt-yourself-doing-your-computer-job","label":"Or: How To Not Hurt Yourself Doing Your Computer Job","html_id":"or-how-to-not-hurt-yourself-doing-your-computer-job","implicit":true,"key":"yGrCMitUgu"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note: None of these links are affiliate links. These are just recommendations I’m sharing from personal experience and lots of internet research I’ve done to accommodate my own medical issues.","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"sHLHgBnPQW"}],"key":"qUglCuLSq8"}],"key":"RhfGgdo6L6"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Most people come to data science (or other computer-based professions) when they’re young and healthy. As a result, at the start of their careers, most data scientists don’t think anything of hunching over a laptop for hours on end, banging away at their little keyboards.","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"GsR4L3Io3H"}],"key":"KnJ3WrsetK"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As time goes on, however, almost everyone eventually realizes this is not a sustainable strategy. Even otherwise healthy people’s wrists, backs, and necks will eventually start to object to this level of abuse. And that’s assuming you don’t have pre-existing medical issues to complicate your journey!","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"NeKZCvXJzJ"}],"key":"wVNjyCAbpG"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"With that in mind, in this reading, I want to detail a series of tools you may find helpful in protecting your body and your ability to work, starting from simple interventions (an external keyboard and monitor) up through medium interventions (better desk chair, adjustable desk, monitor arm, ergonomic keyboards), and finally, tools that allow for people with more serious medical constraints — such as an inability to use a keyboard — to continue to work effectively.","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"v21SIxbukD"}],"key":"eH9dSC2kGD"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Simple Interventions","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"MXMEvaqWhy"}],"identifier":"simple-interventions","label":"Simple Interventions","html_id":"simple-interventions","implicit":true,"key":"eI876Yo7kc"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"External Monitor, Keyboard, and Mouse","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"key":"BHJADXwmAF"}],"identifier":"external-monitor-keyboard-and-mouse","label":"External Monitor, Keyboard, and Mouse","html_id":"external-monitor-keyboard-and-mouse","implicit":true,"key":"vDsPKEGO5J"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If nothing else, I’m a ","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"jQDfQVtLfN"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"huge","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"uEoBErV9Jv"}],"key":"VJYH4VXH5Q"},{"type":"text","value":" advocate of anyone who works at their computer a lot getting an external monitor, keyboard, and mouse. They’re relatively inexpensive and probably the most beneficial interventions available.","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"YXyqjB0bbK"}],"key":"iMaae2bKyP"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When looking at monitors, bear in mind you shouldn’t spend more than $250 if you don’t want to. Many monitors have really high resolutions, refresh rates, and color fidelity for gamers or professional photographers. But as of 2024, you can pretty easily get a 24\" HD-resolution display for $150 and a 27\" display for $200-250. Those aren’t cutting-edge specs and may be a little less sharp than your laptop screen, but the real estate you gain more than compensates.","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"gmXR2l4jlX"}],"key":"rBR8FSpMz0"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Keyboards and external mice, similarly, are a dime a dozen. And in combination, a monitor, keyboard, and mouse that allows you to sit up straight and look forward are probably the single most impactful changes you can make to your routine to protect your body.","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"key":"rrQJ8qGAuM"}],"key":"FPo0Qqi9W4"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Once you have these, make sure you use them correctly — if you search for “good ergonomics for computers,” you’ll find plenty of resources. The ","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"key":"KfUsto9IGt"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"top","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"key":"hzzDi5017W"}],"key":"KDZ8Oj56Xy"},{"type":"text","value":" of the monitor should be a couple inches below your eye level, the monitor should be roughly arm length from you, and your elbows should be about level with your keyboard. Just put a book under the monitor if it’s too low and doesn’t have its own arm.","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"key":"HecsMqNAs1"}],"key":"c1Hi0BdQwz"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A Good Chair","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"key":"ejSq87LjHm"}],"identifier":"a-good-chair","label":"A Good Chair","html_id":"a-good-chair","implicit":true,"key":"Lp58JsxOML"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A good chair can also be a really impactful intervention (depending on what you’re starting with). ","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"CO1A3zU3tl"},{"type":"link","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WQEkEfQs5vs","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Lots of youtube videos on these","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"AlQPZX1eTX"}],"urlSource":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WQEkEfQs5vs","key":"ZAcYEeXp4q"},{"type":"text","value":", though it’s always better if you can try a chair before buying.","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"pGPIBgkfuE"}],"key":"tdKvGk5zcl"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Don’t Zone Out","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"key":"DALYt1oRts"}],"identifier":"dont-zone-out","label":"Don’t Zone Out","html_id":"dont-zone-out","implicit":true,"key":"Tgito8XFdC"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It’s easy when working at your computer to zone out and just work non-stop for extended periods. But taking quick breaks — spending a minute every 20 looking at something far away to let your eyes focus at a different distance, and/or standing and moving around every 20 minutes if you can — can be hugely beneficial.","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"key":"H4rb8bfSRi"}],"key":"H6NvcYnAdK"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"To help you remember to follow these practices, consider a program that gives you little reminders to look away from your monitor or stand up occasionally like ","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"rsPB5AvBj5"},{"type":"link","url":"https://breaktimer.app/","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Break Timer","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"eyThz80ypz"}],"urlSource":"https://breaktimer.app/","key":"zS9qbtBq7b"},{"type":"text","value":" or ","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"h6QL6BXNY9"},{"type":"link","url":"https://apps.apple.com/us/app/time-out-break-reminders/","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Time Out","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"LA9Iz9orPX"}],"urlSource":"https://apps.apple.com/us/app/time-out-break-reminders/","key":"s4kyE887hp"},{"type":"text","value":". Fitness trackers like an Apple Watch or Fitbit can also remind you if you’ve been sitting for more than 20 minutes to move.","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"aVWrj81A3Q"}],"key":"GQx8UB4XdC"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Medium Interventions","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"Cu1a9imBMq"}],"identifier":"medium-interventions","label":"Medium Interventions","html_id":"medium-interventions","implicit":true,"key":"LT5jNycVrk"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"OK, so you got the keyboard and monitor, and it doesn’t feel like enough. What next?","position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"key":"ed6KHzhJZN"}],"key":"JFDL3xncEP"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Here are a few next steps, depending on what’s causing you the most issues.","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"key":"TSQTNmGNit"}],"key":"Kjd0iFBYZr"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Ergonomic Keyboards and Mice","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"qlr7lgadnZ"}],"identifier":"ergonomic-keyboards-and-mice","label":"Ergonomic Keyboards and Mice","html_id":"ergonomic-keyboards-and-mice","implicit":true,"key":"RVAjTjBrLZ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you are experiencing wrist pain or find yourself slumping forward because your shoulders are being pulled together and forwards by your hands both reaching to the keyboard in the middle of your desk, consider a split keyboard — they’re ","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"hmw4WGIBgW"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"wonderful","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"UrblfsKSMo"}],"key":"NinT5KA6KD"},{"type":"text","value":". The easiest entry point for these is the ","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"lusS1VxSeV"},{"type":"link","url":"https://kinesis-ergo.com/keyboards/freestyle2-keyboard/","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Kinesis Freestyle2","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"rgPqq1dtTK"}],"urlSource":"https://kinesis-ergo.com/keyboards/freestyle2-keyboard/","key":"YRWrdtJW8W"},{"type":"text","value":" (I used it for years, about $100 for new ones, and refurbished ones for $55 in 2024). If you have money, they have some other models with clickier keys and other things people like, but in my experience, the gains are marginal compared to the jump from “regular keyboard to split keyboard.” I ","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"JndIX0G1ch"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"would","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"CfgJl1f9xs"}],"key":"W53zuhRcHF"},{"type":"text","value":" recommend the tent arms and wrist pads if you can get them.","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"NIb2iyTtkC"}],"key":"CMg51eel6b"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The world of ergonomic keyboards goes keep, though, and there are other things you can get if you have the money. For example, some keyboards are curved so the distance from fingers to keys is the same everywhere, have keys where each finger gets a column of letters (ortho-linear keyboards) so they don’t have to move side to side, and some keyboards have buttons for your thumbs (so you don’t have to, say, stretch your pinky to reach the shift key). If your issues are back and neck-related, these may not be that helpful, but if your issues are wrist-related (e.g., RSI), this can reduce problematic finger movement a lot but take a little adjustment to the different key layouts. Examples include:","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"LGXl41E5SI"}],"key":"IEkQGgQbIU"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":47